=== Critical response ===
The [[review_aggregator|review aggregator]] website [[Rotten_Tomatoes|Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 94% approval rating for the second season with an average rating of 7.84/10, based on 24 reviews. The website's consensus reads, "With distinctive visuals and a terrific cast, ''The Flash'' remains one of the strongest comic book shows on television."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/flash/s02/ |title=The Flash: Season 2 |date=2019-12-09 |website=[[Rotten_Tomatoes|Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango_(company)|Fandango]] |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215090357/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/flash/s02/ |archive-date=2018-12-15 |access-date=2018-12-15|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Metacritic|Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned the season a score of 81 out of 100, based on 4 reviews, indicating "universal acclaim".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-flash-2014/season-2 |title=The Flash (2014) : Season 2 |website=[[Metacritic|Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS_Interactive|CBS Interactive]] |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004133606/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-flash-2014/season-2 |archive-date=2015-10-04 |access-date=2015-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref>

Reviewing for [[Collider_(website)|Collider]], Dave Trumbore gave the season premiere a rating of 4 stars out of 5, saying, "All in all, a very good way to start season two after the strong run of season one."<ref name="collider S02E1 review" /> Mike Cecchini of ''[[Den_of_Geek!|Den of Geek!]]'' meanwhile rated the episode 3.5 stars out of 5, criticizing the episode's "unsettled" and "rushed" nature. He felt that the episode "seems so focused on getting this season off to a running start that it [...] doesn't give events time to breathe."<ref name="201Cecchini">{{Cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/the-flash/249580/the-flash-season-2-premiere-review-the-man-who-saved-central-city |title=The Flash Season 2 Premiere Review: The Man Who Saved Central City |last=Cecchini |first=Mike |date=2015-10-06 |website=Den of Geek! |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218054522/https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/the-flash/249580/the-flash-season-2-premiere-review-the-man-who-saved-central-city |archive-date=2018-12-18 |access-date=2018-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Erik Kain of ''[[Forbes|Forbes]]'' noted a "very big piece" missing in the absence of Harrison Wells, but felt that the episode was "an excellent start to the sophomore season of the CW’s best super hero show."<ref name="201Kain">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/10/06/the-flash-season-2-premiere-review-the-man-who-saved-central-city/#36e99069395c |title='The Flash' Season 2 Premiere Review: 'The Man Who Saved Central City' |last=Kain |first=Erik |date=2015-10-06 |website=[[Forbes|Forbes]] |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218054547/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/10/06/the-flash-season-2-premiere-review-the-man-who-saved-central-city/#36e99069395c |archive-date=2018-12-18 |access-date=2018-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Although Henry Allen's abrupt exit was a common point of criticism amongst reviewers, Trumbore nevertheless felt that it was "a small price to pay for an otherwise cohesive, entertaining, and emotionally satisfying episode."<ref name="collider S02E1 review" /><ref name="201Kain" /><ref name="201Cecchini" />

The episode "Welcome to Earth-2" received a number of positive reviews. Erik Kain said that it was "''The Flash'' at its best. An engaging, funny, scary episode that hits all the right notes from start to finish."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2016/02/10/the-flash-season-2-episode-13-review-earth-two-where-all-of-barrys-fantasies-come-true/#32ed152457a9 |title='The Flash' Season 2, Episode 13 Review: Earth Two, Where All Of Barry's Dreams Come True |last=Kain |first=Erik |date=2016-02-10 |website=[[Forbes|Forbes]] |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714123334/http://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2016/02/10/the-flash-season-2-episode-13-review-earth-two-where-all-of-barrys-fantasies-come-true/#32ed152457a9 |archive-date=2016-07-14 |access-date=2018-12-16|language=en-US}}</ref> [[IGN|IGN]]'s Jesse Schedeen rated it 9.7 out of 10, praising the concept of Earth-2, Barry's dramatic moments, the depiction of Deathstorm, Killer Frost, and Reverb, but criticized the need to kill off Reverb so soon. He concluded, "''The Flash'' delivered one of its best episodes yet as Barry and friends took a hilarious but emotional trip to Earth-2."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2016/02/10/the-flash-welcome-to-earth-2-review |title=The Flash: "Welcome to Earth-2" Review |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |date=2016-02-09 |website=[[IGN|IGN]] |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310084000/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/02/10/the-flash-welcome-to-earth-2-review |archive-date=2018-03-10 |access-date=2018-12-16|language=en-US}}</ref> Angelica Jade Bastién of ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]'' said the episode "marries incredible action sequences, amazing direction by Millicent Shelton, some of the cast's best acting (particularly from Candice Patton and Grant Gustin), lots of heart, and just the right number of nods to the comics. It is undoubtedly the best episode of the season, and just may be the best episode of ''The Flash'' yet."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/02/flash-recap-season-2-episode-13.html |title=The Flash Recap: Through the Looking Glass |last=Bastién |first=Angelica Jade |date=2016-02-10 |website=Vulture |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204094617/http://www.vulture.com/2016/02/flash-recap-season-2-episode-13.html |archive-date=2017-02-04 |access-date=2018-12-16|language=en-US}}</ref> Dave Trumbore rated the episode 4 stars out of 5, saying, "This was an absolutely insane episode of ''The Flash'', and that's saying something since this show is normally fast-paced and full of Easter eggs even on a relatively slow week."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-flash-recap-welcome-to-earth-2/ |title='The Flash' Recap: "Welcome to Earth-2'' - It's Zoom's World and We're Just Living In It |last=Trumbore |first=Dave |date=2016-02-09 |website=Collider |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615214450/http://collider.com/the-flash-recap-welcome-to-earth-2/ |archive-date=2018-06-15 |access-date=2018-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment_Weekly|Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Jonathon Dornbush praised the scene where Barry talks to his Earth-2 doppelgänger's mother over phone, saying Gustin "has proved mightily adept at tackling Barry's grief, hope, and the many other emotions swirling around in regard to his mother and her death."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/recap/the-flash-season-2-episode-13/ |title='The Flash' recap: Doppelgangers, death, and more drama await on Earth-2 |last=Dornbush |first=Jonathon |date=2016-02-10 |website=[[Entertainment_Weekly|Entertainment Weekly]] |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403114649/http://ew.com/recap/the-flash-season-2-episode-13/ |archive-date=2018-04-03 |access-date=2018-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Scott Von Doviak of ''[[The_A.V._Club|The A.V. Club]]'' said, "Since its return from hiatus, ''The Flash'' has been sluggish and morose, and the Zoom arc has fizzled. 'Welcome to Earth-2' jump-starts both the storyline and the season as a whole [...and] is just about as good as ''The Flash'' gets."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-flash-visits-earth-2-in-a-whirlwind-episode-that-jo-1798186588 |title=The Flash visits Earth-2 in a whirlwind episode that jolts the season back to life |last=Doviak |first=Scott Von |date=2016-02-09 |website=[[The_A.V._Club|The A.V. Club]] |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218143615/https://tv.avclub.com/the-flash-visits-earth-2-in-a-whirlwind-episode-that-jo-1798186588 |archive-date=2018-12-18 |access-date=2018-12-17|language=en-US}}</ref>

Reviewing the season finale, Allison Keene of Collider directed specific praise to Gustin's performance, saying "Sometimes a great TV performer can come out of an already fantastic episode, but occasionally an actor can rise above the material, proving that even though the writers have let them down, the actor is going to make the most of what they’ve been given. That’s exactly where we find ourselves with ''The Flash''{{'}}s head-scratching finale, which capped off a largely enjoyable but ultimately uneven second season. What has never been in doubt, though, is star Grant Gustin’s ability to convince viewers that this all makes sense in an emotional, earnest, and often light-hearted way."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/tv-performer-of-the-week-grant-gustin-the-flash/ |title=TV Performer of the Week: Grant Gustin, 'The Flash' |last=Keene |first=Allison |date=2016-05-27 |website=Collider |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216104238/http://collider.com/tv-performer-of-the-week-grant-gustin-the-flash |archive-date=2018-12-16 |access-date=2018-12-16|language=en-US}}</ref> In his review for ''[[Nerdist|Nerdist]]'', Joseph McCabe concluded, "For all this season's faults, most of which came from repeating the major villain arc of season one, [...] there were moments in the last handful of episodes where Barry demonstrated more independent thought than the show often allows him. Coming up with his own ideas, for example, to defeat the villain of the week rather than relying on his friends at STAR Labs. That's the Barry I want to see more of in season three.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nerdist.com/the-flash-season-finale-review-the-race-of-his-life/ |title=THE FLASH SEASON FINALE REVIEW: "THE RACE OF HIS LIFE" |last=McCabe |first=Joseph |date=2016-05-25 |website=Nerdist |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218054847/https://nerdist.com/the-flash-season-finale-review-the-race-of-his-life/ |archive-date=2018-12-18 |access-date=2018-12-17 |language=en-US}}</ref>

A number of critics felt that the season as a whole suffered from the standards set by its predecessor, calling it "uneven" and criticizing the handling of the season's main villain. Collider's Kayti Burt gave the season 3 stars out of 5, saying, "''The Flash'' finished off an uneven season with an uneven finale that couldn’t overcome the burden of an underdeveloped, illogical villain. With Zoom, ''The Flash'' fell victim to a common drama mistake of a contemporary TV era: it prioritized the plot twist over the well-developed character arc."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-flash-season-2-finale-recap-the-race-of-his-life/ |title='The Flash' Season 2 Finale Recap: "The Race of His Life" |last=Burt |first=Kayti |date=2016-05-24 |website=Collider |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407033532/http://collider.com/the-flash-season-2-finale-recap-the-race-of-his-life |archive-date=2018-04-07 |access-date=2018-12-16|language=en-US}}</ref> Jeff Jensen of ''[[Entertainment_Weekly|Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the season a "B-" grade, calling it "certifiably slumptacular" and said that the "bold" introduction of the multiverse did not meet his expectations. Jensen praised Barry's onscreen rapport with Joe but felt it was underutilized due to the introduction of Joe's biological son Wally, and criticized Barry's romantic fixation for Iris. He also criticized Zoom, saying, "He began as an alluring mystery but lost zip over time" and once his identity was revealed, "became a weak embodiment of generic villainy".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://ew.com/article/2016/05/25/flash-season-2-review/ |title=The Flash season 2 review |last=Jensen |first=Jeff |date=2017-03-28 |work=[[Entertainment_Weekly|Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=2018-12-02 |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215090244/https://ew.com/article/2016/05/25/flash-season-2-review/ |archive-date=2018-12-15|language=en-US}}</ref> Jesse Schedeen gave the entire season a rating of 8.6 out of 10, explaining, "This season met and occasionally even exceeded the heights of its predecessor. But it was also a more uneven and ultimately more flawed experience in the end."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2016/06/01/the-flash-season-2-review |title=The Flash: Season 2 Review |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |date=2016-06-01 |website=[[IGN|IGN]] |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026160323/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/06/01/the-flash-season-2-review |archive-date=2016-10-26 |access-date=2016-12-15|language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Accolades ===
''The Flash'' was included on multiple Best/Top TV Shows of 2015 lists, ranking on ''[[The_Salt_Lake_Tribune|The Salt Lake Tribune]]''{{'}}s (4th), ''[[Omaha_World-Herald|Omaha World-Herald]]''{{'}}s (7th), and ''[[IndieWire|IndieWire]]''{{'}}s (10th), as well as on un-ranked lists of ''[[Criticwire|Criticwire]]'' and ''[[Variety_(magazine)|Variety]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-the-top-10-best-tv-shows-of-2015 |title=Best of 2015: Television Critic Top Ten Lists |date=2015-12-08 |website=Metacritic |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706184930/http://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-the-top-10-best-tv-shows-of-2015 |archive-date=2016-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> In its second season, ''The Flash'' was nominated for 20 awards, winning five. The series was nominated for three [[Saturn_Awards|Saturn Awards]], winning [[Saturn_Award_for_Best_Superhero_Adaptation_Television_Series|Best Superhero Adaption Television Series]] for the second year in a row.<ref name="42nd Saturn Awards" /> The show was also nominated for three [[Leo_Awards|Leo Awards]], winning again for Best Visual Effects in a Dramatic Series for the episode "Gorilla Warfare".<ref name="LeoAwards" /> At the [[2016_Teen_Choice_Awards|2016 Teen Choice Awards]], the show gained six nominations with Gustin winning for Choice TV Actor: Fantasy/Sci-Fi.<ref name="2016 Teen Choice Awards" />

